 competition, and official corruption. While patronage networks are often seen as a parasite on the formal institutions of state, Hillman shows that patronage politics actually help China's political system function. In a system characterized by fragmented authority, personal power relations, and bureaucratic indiscipline, patronage networks play a critical role in facilitating policy coordination and bureaucratic bargaining. They also help to regulate political competition within the state, which reduces the potential for open conflict. Understanding patronage networks is essential for understanding the resilience of the Chinese state through decades of change. Power and Patronage is filled with rich and fascinating accounts of the machinations of patronage networks and their role in the ruthless and sometimes violent competition for political power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLocal governmentxChina, Southwest. 0aLocal governmentzChina, Southwest. 0aPatronage, PoliticalxChina, Southwest. 0aPatronage, PoliticalzChina, Southwest. 0aSocial networksxChina, Southwest. 0aSocial networkszChina, Southwest. 0aVillagesxChina, Southwest. 0aVillageszChina, Southwest. 4aChinese politics. 4acorruption. 4ainformal institutions. 4alocal governance. 4aparty-state resilience. 4apatronage networks. 4arural China. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Local.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791618zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791618.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles